iption":"With real handler and persistent queue in test storage, send the same event ID twice (including near-simultaneous requests). Assert exactly one persisted queue entry and appropriate second-response behavior per spec.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.1,"Integration":0.8,"System":0.1,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":6,"description":"When the queue reports it is full, the handler returns 503 with a Retry-After header.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"Primary failure boundary is mapping queue-capacity signal/error to HTTP response contract. This needs handler+queue-module wiring, not real OS/network. Higher levels are disqualified because behavior text is about queue-reported state translation, which in-process integration can faithfully reproduce.","test_description":"Use handler wired to queue implementation/test double that enters full state. Submit valid webhook and assert HTTP 503 plus `Retry-After` header, and assert no successful enqueue side effect.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.18,"Integration":0.76,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.0,"Workflow":0.0}},{"behavior_id":7,"description":"The persistent queue actually enforces its configured capacity limit and rejects events that would exceed it.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"This validates persistence-layer enforcement (stateful capacity accounting), which is beyond a pure function but does not require external OS/network/subprocess. Local DB/filesystem-backed queue integration is sufficient. System is rejected because no real external infrastructure is required by the behavior text.","test_description":"Instantiate the real persistent queue against local test storage with a small configured capacity. Enqueue up to limit, then one extra event; assert rejection/error on overflow and unchanged persisted depth.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_